courses.learning_outcomes:
After completing the course, students should be able to:

1. describe the key elements of an effective and empathic engagement with patients (affective, cognitive, somatic);

2. appreciate aspects of distressed or distancing empathy leading to over-arousal (sympathetic distress) or aversion;

3. appraise contexts and factors leading to empathic failure, distressed or distancing empathy;

4. understand the neural network of empathy and how empathy (towards self and others, in personal and professional contexts) translates into sustainable professional practice and life satisfaction;

5. understand the importance of cultivating reflective practice to maintain effective empathy in professional context; and

6. understand and practice the process of reflective practice: reflection on content and process (context, self), reflection in action (real-time awareness), reflection on action (retrospective).

After completing this course, students should be able to:
1) describe the patient's presentation by integrating biological, psychological and social aspects of illness;
2) describe the role of the family doctor and health professionals in the community and the key elements of an effective doctor patient relationship;
3) interact and gather information from the family regarding pregnancy, childbirth and child care;
4) describe the health, social and developmental issues of a child from birth to 3 months; and
5) demonstrate skills in reflective writing

After completing the course, students should be able to:

1. describe the structure and function of various biomolecules that build up a cell;
2. outline the metabolism of these biomolecules and its integrative control;
3. explain the principles in molecular biology and medical genetics, and
4. appreciate how molecular genetics and genomic medicine advance medical treatment to patients.

Towards the end of the year, students are expected to:
1. have competent history-taking skills, allowing them to record accurately patients’ past medical problems and present medical complaints;
2. be able to perform proper physical examination of the major systems, to elicit accurate signs and to interpret results of simple investigations such as laboratory reports, ECG and radiological images;
3. develop effective communication skills, enabling them to understand/elicit patients’ concerns and expectations;
4. be able to summarize findings from history-taking and physical examination, and to be able to put together a list of differential diagnosis and/or problems list; and
5. understand the need for continual learning during both their student years, throughout their medical careers.

After completing the course, students should be able to:

1. practice communication with respect, knowledge, and skills related to clients' age, class, color, culture, disability, ethnicity, family structure, gender, marital status, national origin, race, religion, sex, and sexual orientation;
2. reflect and develop the sensitivity to personal values, beliefs, bias, and prejudice related to a person past socialization;
3. explore the health care or related policy context and social welfare system in Hong Kong via the selected topics; and
4. identify current social policy, relevant legislation, and political, social, and/or economic systems and their impacts on medical service delivery.

By the end of the course, students should be able to:
1. perform basic life support re-visit;
2. take a proper history, document and present effectively;
3. assess a patient's neurological status and document properly on a neuro-observation chart;
4. insert of nasogastric tube;
5. perform peripheral vascular examination;
6. use ophthalmoscope;
7. develop communication skills;
8. interpret ECG; and
9. perform physical examination.

Following completion of this course, students are expected to:
1. recognize the common clinical presentations of patients with surgical problems and recognize those with serious or life threatening conditions;
2. make a reasonable differential diagnosis based on the clinical presentation and know appropriate diagnostic investigations necessary for the care of such patients;
3. know the anatomical, physiological and pathological basis of common diseases and disorders in the surgical patients;
4. interpret common diagnostic tests (laboratory and radiological) relevant to these common diseases; and
5. outline a management plan for the care of patients presenting with common surgical conditions.

After completing the course, students should be able to:

1. describe normal physical and psychosocial developments of a child from birth to 3 years old and demonstrate awareness of common health problems in child health;
2. appraise a child's health and development and the family adjustment in terms of socioeconomic factors, health beliefs and health care provision;
3. outline key health care provisions and the role of health professionals in child health; and
4. evaluate the needs of the child and family and the role, skills and attitude of health professionals and community care facilities.

By the end of the course, students should be able to:

1. understand basic infection control concepts with the aim of protecting patients and healthcare workers;
2. able to choose and use appropriate personal protective equipment;
3. articulate different microbial causes of human infectious diseases, their diagnostic approaches and clinical management strategies; and

4. critically analyse the problems of antimicrobial resistance and potential solutions.

After completing the course, students should be able to:

1. describe and illustrate communication strategies used to enhance the patient-doctor relationship;
2. demonstrate and explain close reading and listening to the patient narrative and experience of illness;
3. understand types of illness trajectories and the role of doctor in patient-centred care; and
4. evaluate and contrast the health, social, family and developmental issues of a child in the first year of life.

After completing the course in Medicine Year 3, students should be able to:
1. revise anatomical structure in major regions of the human body;
2. apply this anatomical knowledge to radiological imaging;
3. appreciate clinical relevance of this anatomical knowledge;
4. apply relevant anatomical knowledge to basic clinical skills; and
5. perform basic physical examination skills

After completion of this course, medical students should be able to:

1. acquire basic pathologic principles;
2. understand important pathologic definitions;
3. appreciate the range of pathologic services provided by Anatomical Pathology, Chemical Pathology, Forensic pathology and Microbiology;
4. apply appropriate pathologic studies in the clinical management of a patient.

Advanced Clinical Skills
• Students will know the components of a basic medical history and know how to take a basic medical history from a patient;
• Students will know how to perform a physical examination for the following systems: Cardiovascular, respiratory and abdomen.

Forensic Pathology
• Students are expected to learn the changes of the human body after death;
• Students will be familiar with forensic investigations of death, examination of wounds, forensic aspects of asphyxia, injuries, sexual offences, abortion, and child abuse.

Microbiology
• Students will be equipped with essential infection control knowledge necessary for clinical attachments;
• Students will understand standard and transmission-based precautions, use of common personal protection equipment, precautions of sharps injury and blood and body fluid exposure and disinfection and sterilization;
• Students will have basic concepts on hospital hygiene, staff vaccination and sickness report;
• Students can perform hand hygiene, don and doff personal protection equipment.

By the end of the Module, students are expected to be able to:
1. apply the principles and methods of studying health problems in population groups;
2. list the major causes of mortality and morbidity in Hong Kong, including communicable and non-communicable diseases, and describe strategies of prevention and control of these problems;
3. describe the organization of health care system, health services and medical practice in Hong Kong;
4. describe the principles and practice of occupational and environmental medicine;
5. apply the principles and methods of epidemiology in health care practice;
6. adopt a person centred family medicine approach to clinical consultation and evidence based medicine;
7. apply a hypothetical deductive approach in diagnoses formulation, demonstrate management of presenting condition and deliver first line management of common acute and chronic problems in primary care;
8. counsel patients using a lifestyle behavioural approach to promote health in community settings; and
9. explain the role and interactions of health and social issues and resources in the community.

1. Acquire a core of basic knowledge that is commensurate with the amount of exposure students have to paediatrics, in particular clinical presentation, aetiology and pathology, principles of management, prevention and psycho-social consequences of common disorders seen in Hong Kong.
2. Recognise that (i) childhood is but one part of the human life span and that many problems of children have their origins before birth; (ii) given improved methods of care, more children are surviving chronic illness into adulthood with important medical, educational and social consequences; and (iii) childhood illness can and often does lead to problematic outcomes and consequences in adult life.
3. Use competently the clinical method to identify and plan to resolve clinical problems through:
• reliable, relevant and sensitive history taking, relating effectively to parents and children;
• thorough, accurate and gentle physical examination;
• concise evaluation of the presenting clinical problem;
• orderly planning of any further diagnostic procedures which might be indicated to establish a diagnosis;
• appreciation of the PRINCIPLES of treatment (including the roles of other health professionals, e.g., speech therapists, physiotherapists, social workers, clinical psychologists in management);
• understanding the principles underlying FOLLOW-UP assessment in order to appreciate the natural or assisted course of a clinical problem;
• awareness of the psycho-social consequences (the impact of illness on behaviour, education, family life) of illness and its simple medico-legal consequences; and
• appreciation of a broad, holistic and sensitive outlook towards the total health of individuals and communities.
4. Demonstrate skill in communicating with a child, parents and fellow professional workers, including traits of empathy, patience, kindness and counselling ability.
5. Provide at the bedside an orderly presentation of a clinical problem.
6. Appreciate the manner in which paediatric problems, their management and prevention interrelate with the practices of other disciplines, especially community medicine, psychiatry and obstetrics.

Students should be able to:
1. Deliver news about serious illnesses to patients and families in a clear, sensitive, and honest manner;
2. Anticipate, interpret, and respond appropriately to one's own, patients’, families’, and healthcare team’s emotions;
3. Demonstrate the skills of applying relevant ethical principles when communicating with patients and families;
4. Demonstrate effective communication skills that foster intra- and inter-disciplinary team collaboration;
5. Reflect and critically appraise their own and others’ communication skills as lifelong learners.
